This is a '''list of hazing deaths in the Philippines'''. This is not an exhaustive list. Inclusion in this list requires that the incident was described by the media as a hazing-related death. Majority of deaths in this list include but is not limited to cases that involve [[fraternities]].
The first reported hazing death in the Philippines was that of Gonzalo Mariano Albert, a [[University of the Philippines Diliman]] student and a [[Upsilon Sigma Phi]] neophyte. He died in 1954.
The death of Leonardo Villa in 1991 led to the passage of the [[Anti-Hazing Act of 1995]].<ref name="scpunishes"/>
== List == ===1950s–1990s=== {| class="wikitable sortable" !width=12%| Date of death !width=14%| Victim !width=12%| Organization !width=12%| Institution !width=50% class="unsortable"| Notes |- |{{dts|July 18, 1954}} | {{sortname|Gonzalo Mariano|Albert|nolink=1}} |[[Upsilon Sigma Phi]] |[[University of the Philippines Diliman]] |The first recorded hazing death in the Philippines.<ref name="kapatiran">{{cite news|title=AnimatED: Kapatiran ng kamatayan|trans-title=AnimatED: Brotherhood of death|url=https://www.rappler.com/views/animated/184005-fraternity-brotherhood-death-hazing-horacio-castillo|accessdate=4 October 2017|work=Rappler|date=2 October 2017|language=Filipino}}</ref> Mariano was allegedly mauled by other fraternity members after failing to do an assigned task.<ref name="gmaup">{{cite news|title=Casualties of frat-related violence in UP|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/content/59204/casualties-of-frat-related-violence-in-up/story/|accessdate=6 October 2017|work=GMA News|date=5 September 2007}}</ref>
Philippine President [[Ramon Magsaysay]] created the Castro Committee on October 1954 to investigate the death. The eponymous committee was headed by [[Executive Secretary (Philippines)|Executive Secretary]] [[Fred Ruiz Castro]] joined by UP faculty members Arturo Garcia and V. Lontok. It submitted a 116-page report to Magsaysay find hazing to be the cause of Albert's death and also recommended the expulsion of 4 officers of Upsilon, suspension of 25 members for one year, suspension of 19 neophytes for a semester, and a reprimand the reprimand of 3 other members. It also called for reforms on university regulation on fraternities and sororities and the prohibition of all forms of physical initiation. The report was not acted upon.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Abinales|first1=Patricio|title=A hazing|url=https://www.rappler.com/thought-leaders/99091-up-1954-albert-hazing-case-castro-committee-report|accessdate=4 October 2017|work=Rappler|date=12 July 2012}}</ref> |- |1967<!--http://www.pinoyfraternity.com/index.php?showtopic=3457 says August 13 but that's a forum.--> | {{sortname|Ferdinand|Tabtab|nolink=1}} |[[Alpha Phi Omega (Philippines)|Alpha Phi Omega]] |[[University of the Philippines Diliman]] |Ferdinand Tabtab<ref name="abs-cbn">{{cite news|title=Deaths Caused by Hazing|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/news/multimedia/infographic/09/27/17/deaths-caused-by-hazing|accessdate=4 October 2017|work=ABS-CBN News|agency=ABS-CBN Investigative and Research Group|date=27 September 2017}}</ref> is the first recorded hazing death in the history of the fraternity.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Evangelista|first1=Oscar|title=Icons and Institutions: Essays on the History of the University of the Philippines, 1952-2000|date=2008|publisher=UP Press|isbn=9715425690|page=163|url=https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=v_DqOmhqtjIC&lpg=PA163&ots=NCtSZkx3hG&dq=Ferdinand%20Tabtab%20hazing&pg=PA163#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=4 October 2017}}</ref> |- |{{dts|August 21, 1976}} | {{sortname|Mel|Honasan|nol